p://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>13.6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>13.6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mn>4</mn></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>16</mn></mfrac></math><br />From option, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math>&nbsp; are satisfying the equation.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39070,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$\\left(\\frac{e}{2 m} \\frac{n^2 h}{2 \\pi}\\right)$","$\\left(\\frac{e}{m}\\right) \\frac{n h}{2 \\pi}$","$\\left(\\frac{e}{2 m}\\right) \\frac{n h}{2 \\pi}$","$\\left(\\frac{e}{m}\\right) \\frac{n^2 h}{2 \\pi}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Magnetic moment of the hydrogen atom, when the electron is in $\\mathrm{n}^{\\text {th }}$ excited state, i.e., $n^{\\prime}=(n+1)$\nAs magnetic moment $\\mathrm{M}_{\\mathrm{n}}=\\mathrm{I}_{\\mathrm{n}} \\mathrm{A}=\\mathrm{i}_{\\mathrm{n}}\\left(\\pi \\mathrm{r}_{\\mathrm{n}}^2\\right)$\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& i_n=e V_n=\\frac{m z^2 e^5}{4 \\varepsilon_0^2 n^3 h^3} \\\\\n& r_n=\\frac{n^2 h^2}{4 \\pi^2 k z m e^2}\\left(k=\\frac{1}{4 \\pi \\epsilon_0}\\right)\n\\end{aligned}$\nSolving we get magnetic moment of the hydrogen atom for $\\mathrm{n}^{\\text {th }}$ excited state\n$M_{n^{\\prime}}=\\left(\\frac{e}{2 m}\\right) \\frac{n h}{2 \\pi}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":39026,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>8</mn></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Energy of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>H</mi></math> -atom is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><msup><mi>Z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>/</mo><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>H</mi></math>-atom <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;and for ground state, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><msup><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>e</mi><mi>V</mi></math></p><p>Now for carbon atom (single ionised),&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mfrac><msup><mi>Z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn></math>&nbsp;(given)</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>6</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39083,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$n=2$ to $n=6$","$n=6$ to $n=2$","$n=2$ to $n=1$","$n=1$ to $n=2$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$h v=\\operatorname{Rhcz}^2\\left(\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{n}_1^2}-\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{n}_2^2}\\right)$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2007","image":null},{"id":39047,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$\\frac{27}{20} \\lambda$","$\\frac{16}{25} \\lambda$","$\\frac{25}{16} \\lambda$","$\\frac{20}{27} \\lambda$"],"answer":3,"solution":"When electron jumps from $\\mathrm{M} \\rightarrow \\mathrm{L}$ shell\r\n\r\n$\\frac{1}{\\lambda}=\\mathrm{K}\\left(\\frac{1}{2^{2}}-\\frac{1}{3^{2}}\\right)=\\frac{\\mathrm{K} \\times 5}{36}$\r\n\r\nWhen eletron jumps from $\\mathrm{N} \\rightarrow \\mathrm{L}$ shell\r\n\r\n$\\frac{1}{\\lambda^{\\prime}}=K\\left(\\frac{1}{2^{2}}-\\frac{1}{4^{2}}\\right)=\\frac{K \\times 3}{16}$\r\n\r\nsolving equation (i) and (ii) we get\r\n\r\n$\\lambda^{\\prime}=\\frac{20}{27} \\lambda$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39022,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mi>eV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2815</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>eV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>331</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>eV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>27</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>eV</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>r</mi></mfrac><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>m</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>E</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mi>m</mi></math>. Ionization potential <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mfenced><msub><mtext>Mass</mtext><mi>&#956;</mi></msub></mfenced><mi>eV</mi></mrow><mfenced><msub><mtext>Mass</mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></msub></mfenced></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>207</mn><mi>eV</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2815</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>eV</mi></math>.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39010,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>34</mn></mrow></msup><mi>Js</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>34</mn></mrow></msup><mi>Js</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>34</mn></mrow></msup><mi>Js</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>34</mn></mrow></msup><mi>Js</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Energy absorbed is given by,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#916;</mi><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p>Therefore, we get,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p><p>The change in angular momentum</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#916;</mi><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>h</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi>h</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>h</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>34</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38967,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$\\frac{h}{\\pi}$","$\\frac{h}{2 \\pi}$","$8 \\frac{h}{\\pi}$","$2 \\frac{h}{\\pi}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Moment of momentum is $\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{r}} \\times \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{P}}$\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{L}}=\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{r}} \\times \\mathrm{m} \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{v}} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{L}=\\mathrm{mvr}=\\frac{\\mathrm{nh}}{2 \\pi}=\\frac{4 \\mathrm{~h}}{2 \\pi}=\\frac{2 \\mathrm{~h}}{\\pi}\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39014,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["All&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>K</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>P</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi></math> increase.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>K</mi></math> decreases, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi></math> increase.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi></math> decreases, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>K</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi></math> increase.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>K</mi></math> increases, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi></math> decrease"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Total energy of electron is stated as&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mi>Z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>e</mi><mn>4</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>8</mn><msup><mfenced><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>h</mi><msub><mi>&#949;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math>, potential energy&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mi>Z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>e</mi><mn>4</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><msup><mfenced><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>h</mi><msub><mi>&#949;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp;and kinetic energy is given by&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>K</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mi>Z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>e</mi><mn>4</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>8</mn><msup><mfenced><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>h</mi><msub><mi>&#949;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math>.</p><p>So, as electron makes transition to higher level, total energy and potential energy increases due to the negative sign while the kinetic energy of electron decreases.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 2)","image":null}]